&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Hi
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Whilst calculating the number of offspring for a valid (i.e. non
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; extinct and size &gt; 0) specie, the count returns 0.  This is
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; particularly prevalent in large species where the adjusted
fitness
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; becomes quite small comapared with the rest of the other, and
&gt; &gt; usually
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; much less populous, species.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; This becomes even more marked if I boost young species fitness.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; As far as I understand, the offspring is calculated as follows.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; (av adjusted specie fitness) / (total of all species av adjusted
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; fitnesses) * Population size.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; For example, imagine we have 3 species. Specie_1 has 3 members
&gt; &gt; av raw
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; fitness 0.85, Specie_2 has 2 members av raw fitness 0.82 and
&gt; &gt; Specie_3
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; has 145 members with av raw fitness 0f 0.9.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Specie_1(adj) = 0.85/3 = 0.28333
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Specie_2(adj) = 0.82/2 = 0.41
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Specie_3(adj) = 0.9/145 = 0.006
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Specie_1 then generates 61 offspring
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Specie_2 then generates 87 offspring
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Specie_3 then generates 2 offspring
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Not quite 0, but you get the idea.  So even though the largest
&gt; &gt; specie
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; with has best average fitness, its population gets decimated.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; I understand, that large species need to get penalised, but this
&gt; &gt; seems
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; extreme and you are potentially losing a lot of good gemomes.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Ideas/correction/thoughts appreciated.
